<ext_descriptions module_directory="message" schema_file="arm.xml" describe.selects="YES" rcs.date="$Date: 2003/10/31 09:44:36 $" rcs.revision="$Revision: 1.16 $">
	<!-- ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
  Schema: Message_arm
   <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ -->
	<ext_description linkend="Message_arm">
</ext_description>
	<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Message_arm  Type: message_approval_select 
   <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.message_approval_select"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
	<ext_description linkend="Message_arm.message_approval_select">
The approval has the implication that the contents are suitable for the purpose of the message.
<note> The approval of the list of intended recipients of the message is held against Envelope. </note>
	</ext_description>
	<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Message_arm  Type: message_date_time_select 
   <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.message_date_time_select"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
	<ext_description linkend="Message_arm.message_date_time_select">
		<note>
                  <p>
			<express_ref
linkend="date_time_assignment:arm:Date_time_assignment_arm.Date_or_date_time_assignment.role"/>
allows the role of the assigment to be identified, for example, "date
made". 
                      </p>
</note>
	</ext_description>
	<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Message_arm  Type: message_definer_select 
   <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.message_definer_select"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
	<ext_description linkend="Message_arm.message_definer_select">
The message definer is initially defined as an <express_ref linkend="person_organization:arm:Person_organization_arm.Organization"/> or <express_ref linkend="person_organization:arm:Person_organization_arm.Person_in_organization"/>, but provision is made to extend this in higher level modules.
<note number="2"> Another possible message definer is a piece of automatic recording equipment, which will need
the select extending to <express_ref linkend="product_version:arm:Product_version_arm.Product_version"/>.</note>
	</ext_description>
	<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Message_arm  Type: message_security_classification_select 
   <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.message_security_classification_select"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
	<ext_description linkend="Message_arm.message_security_classification_select">
This enables a security classification to be applied to the message as a whole.
<note> The security classification of the collection of information may be higher than any of the individual elements of the message. </note>
	</ext_description>
	<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Message_arm  Type: message_state_select 
   <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.message_state_select"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
	<ext_description linkend="Message_arm.message_state_select">
		<note> The business process for creating, approving and processing a message can be mapped to a state model, hence assigning a series of states to a message allows an audit trail to be produced. </note>
	</ext_description>
	<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Message_arm  Entity: Content_item  
   <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.Content_item"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
   <ext_description linkend="Message_arm.Content_item">
     A <b>Content_item</b> is a reference to any item that can be referenced as part of the message content.
   <note number="1">
     As well as externally defined items such as drawings, photographs, and
     so on, a message can refer to any entity represented in the schema it is
     used in, from products to property values, or actions to task steps. The
     mechanism used gives no interpretation of how the
     <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.Content_item.item_identifier"/>
     is interpreted or how the data is
     accessed. For example, the identifier could be the number of the
     entity in a file that conforms to ISO 10303-21. 
     Interpretation of this entity and its attributes may be
     defined through reference data.
   </note> 
	</ext_description>
	<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Message_arm  Entity: Content_item  Attribute: access_comment 
   <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.Content_item.access_comment"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
   <ext_description linkend="Message_arm.Content_item.access_comment">
     <p>
       the information required to access the data. This may include or imply a
       description that associated entities are accessed as part of the
       message. 
       The value of this attribute need not be specified.
     </p>
     <example number="3">
       <p>
       The following shows a dummy message for referencing a 
       <express_ref linkend="part_and_version_identification:arm:Part_and_version_identification_arm.Part"/>
       which
       brings with it an 
       <express_ref linkend="identification_assignment:arm:Identification_assignment_arm.Identification_assignment"/>
     </p>
       <screen>
         #1=<express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.Message">MESSAGE</express_ref>((#2), $, $, $, $);
         #2=<express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.Content_item">CONTENT_ITEM</express_ref>('"3"', '10303-21', '&lt;access source="10303-21"> 
                                               &lt;use type="<express_ref linkend="identification_assignment:arm:Identification_assignment_arm.Identification_assignment">IDENTIFICATION_ASSIGNMENT</express_ref>"' ref="#4"/>
                                             &lt;/access>');
         #3=<express_ref linkend="part_and_version_identification:arm:Part_and_version_identification_arm.Part">PART</express_ref>
         #4=<express_ref linkend="identification_assignment:arm:Identification_assignment_arm.Identification_assignment">IDENTIFICATION_ASSIGNMENT</express_ref>('123', 'primary-id', $, (#3));
     </screen>
     <p>
       In order to reference
       <express_ref
         linkend="product_identification:arm:Product_identification_arm.Product"/>
       entity may also bring with it any 
       <express_ref
         linkend="identification_assignment:arm:Identification_assignment_arm.Identification_assignment"/>
       that applies to it.
     </p>
   </example>
</ext_description>
	<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Message_arm  Entity: Content_item  Attribute: item_identifier 
   <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.Content_item.item_identifier"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
   <ext_description linkend="Message_arm.Content_item.item_identifier">
     <p>
       the mechanism to reference any entity or object in the message.
     </p>
     <note number="2">The <b>item_identifier</b> should provide a unique reference to the item referred to in the <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.Message"/>.</note>
	</ext_description>
	<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Message_arm  Entity: Content_item  Attribute: item_type 
   <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.Content_item.item_type"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
   <ext_description linkend="Message_arm.Content_item.item_type">
     <p>the type of the item.</p>
     <example number="1">
       A <express_ref
       linkend="product_identification:arm:Product_identification_arm.Product"/>
     in a file that conforms to ISO 10303-21 may be given the type
     'ISO 10303-21 entity'.
     The value of the <express_ref
     linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.Content_item.item_identifier"/>
     attribute would
     then be the object identifier in the file.
   </example>
   <example number="2">
     A log file from built-in test equipment may be given the type
     'equipment log file'.
   </example>
   </ext_description>
	<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Message_arm  Entity: Message  
   <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.Message"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
	<ext_description linkend="Message_arm.Message">
A <b>Message</b> is a collection of information, brought together by an originator (the message definer) for some particular purpose, generally the fulfillment of a process.
A <b>Message</b> is an historical record, intended to be sent using an <express_ref linkend="envelope:arm:Envelope_arm.Envelope"/> and in consequence, is not versioned.
<note number="1"> The same <b>Message</b> can be sent several times using different <express_ref linkend="envelope:arm:Envelope_arm.Envelope">Envelopes</express_ref>. Once it has been sent
once, it cannot be further changed. However it should not remain unsent, since that is to confuse its functions and therefore its meaning with
other entities such as one of the types of document.
</note>
	</ext_description>
	<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Message_arm  Entity: Message  Attribute: id 
   <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.Message.id"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
   <ext_description linkend="Message_arm.Message.id">
     <p>the identifier of the message.</p>
          <note number="2">The identifier should be unique. </note>
	</ext_description>
	<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Message_arm  Entity: Message  Attribute: message_type 
   <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.Message.message_type"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
   <ext_description linkend="Message_arm.Message.message_type">
     <p>
       the general purpose of the message, allowing it to be differentiated
       from other types of message, and so be handled appropriately. The contents
       of this entity are defined through reference data. 
     </p>
     <note number="3"> 
     <p>
       The following gives an example of reference data for
       <b>message_type</b>:
     </p>
     <ul>
       <li>field input	- used to identify data acquired directly from the environment, for example, on a maintenance engineer's palm top;</li>
       <li>synchronization 	- used to indicate that the attached data has been changed in the originator's data base, and should be used to update the recipients database;</li>
       <li>action required	- used to prompt the recipient to respond to the contents of the reports;</li>
       <li>urgent action required - as above, but with a high priority.</li>
     </ul>
   </note>
	</ext_description>
	<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Message_arm  Entity: Message  Attribute: purpose 
   <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.Message.purpose"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
	<ext_description linkend="Message_arm.Message.purpose">
          <p>
            the extended description of the purpose of the message.
            The value of this attribute need not be specified.
          </p>
<note number="4">Using an analogy of e-mail, purpose is equivalent of the text of the message.</note>
	</ext_description>
	<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Message_arm  Entity: Message  Attribute: contains 
   <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.Message.contains"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
	<ext_description linkend="Message_arm.Message.contains">
          the contents of the <b>Message</b>.
</ext_description>
	<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Message_arm  Entity: Message  Attribute: defined_by 
   <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.Message.defined_by"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
	<ext_description linkend="Message_arm.Message.defined_by">
the identification of who 
(<express_ref linkend="person_organization:arm:Person_organization_arm.Organization"/>
or 
<express_ref linkend="person_organization:arm:Person_organization_arm.Person_in_organization"/>)
or what defined the message, that is, identified its purpose and contents.
The value of this attribute need not be specified.
</ext_description>
	<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Message_arm  Entity: Message_relationship  
   <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.Message_relationship"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
	<ext_description linkend="Message_arm.Message_relationship">
A <b>Message_relationship</b> is a link between two related messages. The meaning of the association depends on <b>Message_relationship.role</b>.
<example> If <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.Message.id">Message.id</express_ref>=2 replaces <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.Message.id">Message.id</express_ref>=1, then <b>Message_relationship.related</b> points to <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.Message.id">Message.id</express_ref>=2 and <b>Message_relationship.relating</b> points to <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.Message.id">Message.id</express_ref>=1 with <b>Message_relationship.role</b>="replaces".</example>
	</ext_description>
	<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Message_arm  Entity: Message_relationship  Attribute: related 
   <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.Message_relationship.related"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
	<ext_description linkend="Message_arm.Message_relationship.related">
          the other instance of <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.Message"/> participating in the relationship. If one <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.Message"/> participating in the relationship is dependent upon the other, this attribute shall be the dependent one.
	</ext_description>
	<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Message_arm  Entity: Message_relationship  Attribute: relating 
   <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.Message_relationship.relating"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
	<ext_description linkend="Message_arm.Message_relationship.relating">
one of the instances of <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.Message"/> participating in the relationship.
	</ext_description>
	<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Message_arm  Entity: Message_relationship  Attribute: relation_type
   <express_ref linkend="message:arm:Message_arm.Message_relationship.relation_type"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
	<ext_description linkend="Message_arm.Message_relationship.relation_type">
the role of the message association.
	</ext_description>
</ext_descriptions>
